segments.text: You had to have Texas history.
At least two.
Yeah, I think you had to have Texas history.
You also had to have U.S. history.
And so, I can't remember who taught me U.S. history.
Did you have notes, Nance?
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
I did have notes, Nance.
The one I remember, I had an English professor that taught Shakespeare.
And...
He was very good.
He sat on his desk and had a cigarette hanging out of his mouth, but he could tell he loved the subject.
And, you know, I enjoyed that course.
Remember his name?
That doesn't ring a bell with me.
No, it doesn't.
He wasn't here very long.
Then I had a Spanish professor, very, I thought he was very, very good.
He's extremely unpopular with other students, so, his name was Statham, and you weren't to be here with him.
He was let go the next year.
But when you walked in there,

have done your homework and learned your vocabulary because the first thing he gave you a pop quiz and that was good for me and uh and i learned spanish surprisingly i took a uh i took spanish and german the german wolf walk it do you remember him i didn't think him as being very good teacher georgia joe wilkett yeah and uh
I mean, I didn't learn my German, even though I have a German background, as much as I did my Spanish, and I went on to another semester of Spanish.
How large were the classes in those days?
Except for the lectures, like in freshman chemistry and things like that, from, I would say, 25 to 60.
One thing that, I'm being honest, one thing that really disenchanted me was my
And the professor insulted my intelligence.
He said, you will turn in a 30-page term paper or something like that two days before grades are due in.
And there were 60 people in the class.
You understand what I'm saying?
I mean, no way he can read 60 times 30 pages in that period of time.
So I, I mean, I did what it was deserved.

I went to the library, went just to the library, got a, where it was by, you know, by topic, took out about 10 books or 20, 15 books, checked them out, took them back to my, the night before they were due, set it up in my little typewriter and typed out
I would paraphrase what he was saying, make some transition.
I'd just paraphrase exactly what he was saying, make some stupid transition over to the next section, type it, turn it in, got a B plus on it.
I mean, it taught me these educators are full of bull.
I had no respect for them.
Hardly for people in education majors, hardly.
I mean, if that was, and I spent the whole time talking about, should we have round classrooms, or should we have square classrooms, and oh, it was hogwash.
You know, I mean, and it was, I mean, sorry, but I get on high horse when I talk about that.
All right.
When you came back, did you have a car?
Yes.
My mother and father had gone to Germany, and they left their 41 Plymouth with me.
Made me very popular.
I was very popular.
My brother was back though.
He was married and he was milking cows and trying to get through.
He had a couple of children before he graduated and he kept the car during the week.
My parents left it with me because he was not as compliant as I was.
He was three years older than me.
Very intelligent.
He kept the car and then I got it on weekends.
And I went to every basketball game.
I went all over the state.
I gave rides for the sports information director, coming back, going there.
I filed on the AP wire for him.
I was sports editor of the battalion by my senior year, my life semester here, coach sports editor of the battalion.
Describe the battalion and being on the battalion staff.
What was the battalion like in those days?
was the Inner Sanctum editorial page, I'd say, was more liberal than A&M.
The sports page was, I think, much more service.
The sports page, if we ever took anything off the AP or UPI wire, we felt we were really being lazy and not doing our job.
We felt that there was enough at A&M of interest of other students to communicate, and we wrote a lot of features.
It was a weekly then?
No, five days a week.
I spent eight hours a day on that rascal.
Who was the advisor director?
Roland Bing.
Great.
Roland Bing.
B-I-N-G?
B-I-N-G. And he later became president of Victoria Junior College.
And we were in Goodwin Hall, second floor.
And he would take the battalion and punch it up on, there was a chalkboard.
And he would circle it right out here and tell us what we'd done wrong after we'd written on it.
And I had a ball, it was lovely, you know.
And- Now you weren't planning to be a journalist.
No.
You were just doing it for- No, they ran an advertisement.
I said it was easy for me.
And then we'd go back and say, well, I got my nickname.
I moved into this outfit with Country Higgins, a football player, Walter Norton Country Higgins.
And I found my grades, I could keep up in decent grades without doing much studying or working.
I spent a lot of time in the sack.
He walked in one day and said, Sporty, you've spent so much time in SAC, I'm going to call you SAC.
Well, he's the only one who did that.
So then one day I would go over to the athletic fields.
I'd watch the basketball team practice, football team practice.
I'd even watch the track team practice.
Can you imagine watching the track team practice?
Running around, just running around and laughing.
And so one day I read in the battalion they need sportswriters.
Gee, I'd probably know more about what's going on in sports here than almost anybody on campus.
I'd rather be out there and observe it.
So I went on and volunteered.
And one thing different then, I think, that the battalion could, we, number one, we did not think that we had to arrange the world to our mindset.
We did not take ourselves too seriously.
We had fun.
And

In the sports page, we would take one reporter and say, you're covering the freshman baseball team, you're covering the varsity baseball team, you're covering the freshman track team, varsity track team, and things like that.
And we'd fight for space for those people.
We wanted to give write-ups to Paul Lemming.
I knew Paul.
Oh, Paul Lemming's coming to A&M?
Best hire on the nation, you know.
And so we'd get things like that.
Then we'd interview him when he got here and stuff like that.
Paul says he's got a lot of things written by me.
about him.
Describe the coaches and the kind of people they were, the head coaches.
Well, when it came, Norton was a coach.
Homer Norton.
Homer Norton was a coach, coached the national championship team, won 19 straight games, 39-40.
My father said his handshake was like shaking hands with a dead fish.
He did not like his handshake.
But I think Homer Norton was extremely loyal to his players.
He would do anything to help his players.
He did not give any sports writing moves.
He did not change with the times, though.
Before he came in, he still wanted to run the single wing.
Army, West Point, were playing with plastic helmets.
He was still using helmets.
SMU came in with low-cut shoes, and he was still playing high-top shoes.
Maybe it was a financial situation, I don't know, but he didn't change with the times that way.
He had Bill James.
He had maybe five or six assistant coaches.
There was no strength and conditioning coach as far as I know.
There was a trainer, various ones.
Marty Corot was a basketball coach and baseball coach, no assistants or even a job, doubled up.
Kern Landy was a track coach, assisted voluntarily by Ray Putnam.
He had been here when I was a fish.
What kind of person was Colonel Andy?

Somewhat, I guess, probably irascible, though I have very good memories of him, because when I was a lieutenant in Germany, I'd covered the truck team for him, with him, and Boyle and Bones came over there, and I met them at the Grand Hotel in Nuremberg, two different occasions.
It made me feel real good, because they saw me and came up and threw their arms around
And they hugged me, because I never asked them stupid questions.
I observed, I didn't need to ask questions, I was there watching the practice, and they really seemed to appreciate it.
So, Colonel Andy took me to, let me ride the train with the track team up to the Commerce Track meet in Arkansas, Fayetteville, Arkansas.
Were those men positive influences on the lives of their athletes?
I don't think so, yes.
Yes.
A good friend of mine, Ray Holbrook, a classmate, I would say yes.
Did athletes go to class?
Yes, yes, yes.
Were there any giveaway courses or majors for athletes?
would probably be the closest.
They'd give seven a year, probably PE more.
Some guys I knew had really high GPAs in PE.
I'm not really qualified to answer that question.
But there were a number of athletes that made splendid grades, weren't you?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, sure.
Oh, and the strange thing was the guys you would think were the big linemen, you know, Odell Stolzenberger, Joe Turley, and
Bob Gary, today would be 3.5 students.
We had a three point grade point at that time, not a four point.
So they were 2.5 or whatever, something like that.
And when you reporters were doing your reporting, you wrote it on pads, and then you typed it up.
There wasn't much electronics.
Nothing electronic in that sense.
We'd type it up, and I'd grind it out.
And I could grind out a lot, and I wrote a lot.
Did you go to the out-of-town games?
Oh, yes.
Did you travel with the team, save the basketball?
Sometimes I did, sometimes I didn't.
I would go for fun.
That's when I went with...
where Doug King was the sports information director.
And he'd drive with me up to Dallas and see a basketball game.
We'd drive back that night.
And he was taken advantage of by the guy that the sports information director did not work for the athletic department.
He worked for the information director of A&M.
And Doug was expected, after he'd travel at night, he was expected to be in the office at 8 o'clock the next morning, which was totally unfair.
Who was the guy's name?
Somebody knows.
But everybody says the same thing about him.
He was a very unfair kind of guy to work for.
But the sports information department did not work for the athletic director.
It worked for the university.
All right, now when you come back from the war in the fall of 46, the president of A&M at that point was who?
Gilchrist.
Gilchrist.
Describe him from the student's point of view as president.
Very suspect.
Suspect of what?
Not being in sympathy with the Aggie way of life.
Okay.
What?
No, I say okay.
Being a TCIP background.
Did he?
Not having a great admiration for his engineering ability because he supposedly designed Gilchrist Folly.
Ever heard of Gilchrist Folly?
The Road to Hearn.
Apparently it's not railroad tracks.
And you got there and then you made a 90 degree turn over an overpass over to the other side of the railroad track and made another 90 degree turn to go through Hearn.
And that was known as Gilchrist Folly because he was the head of the Texas Highway Department and that was built.
I doubt if he had anything to do with the design of that.
But he got the blame for it.
Describe as far as you can remember it the
circumstances that led up to and the March on the President's House.
Okay.

It all began when the first thing that the cadets knew, as far as I know, and I, all my classmates were seniors at that time, Cadet Colonel Ed Brandt, Rick Cush, and the battalion came out with the headline, I still, New Code of Corps Enacted to Our Place.
New Code of the Corps.
Code of the Corps, which took away the authority of the senior court and instituted this new organization called the Student Senate.
There had never been a Student Senate to that point.
As far as I know, they did it without any laying the groundwork for the real reason that it really was necessary to do it.
And I'll explain from my point of view, and I wasn't on the inner circle, but all of these veterans coming back, many of them not taking ROTC, not in any way, shape, or form.
People who had been captains, majors, but had never had any college.
Coming back as freshmen, they did not want to get in the Corps and go through fish year and all that stuff in the Corps.
And there were no way for them to be represented within the student government.
They were not part of the
And therefore had no input.
I think the Corps members would have been receptive to that if it had been explained that we've got to make some adjustments.
But the administration, as far as I know, it just hit a bang, an accomplished thing.
And there was a media hubbub gathering in the Corps.
And I was living in that dormitory, kind of running over to the right there, and all of a sudden a talk show started talking about a march.
They followed the Corps out just before midnight and marched over to that President's home by Savisa.
And they walked up, some of them, not the cadet colonel and not Rick Hoech, not some of the higher strength people, and knocked on his door.
He came to the door, in a bathrobe at least, maybe a night shirt, and they walked up and threw their senior rank at his feet.
Then everybody dispersed and went back to their rooms.
Ed Grant, Rick Hush, and a few others did not participate in that.
So there was a senior class meeting, which I attended.
They held a vote in the old British way, parting, standing, moving over and so on.
And I am proud of this.
I'll be very proud of this.
They came to Rick Cush and they said that we've got to recommend to Rick that he resign his commission as the senior class's classmate.
And I thought, that's Rick Cush's business, not their business.
He doesn't want to do it, he doesn't want to do it.
Everybody, I was the only one who voted against that.
I mean, looking back, it took some guts of courage.
I was all alone over there.
Everybody else was over here.
But I'm with individuals.
I thought, hey, that's his individual right.
He'll do it.
He thinks he's right.
And so I basically voted with the administration.
But then a couple of days later, they had a knee that came out.
You would go and talk to your senior branch advisor about how you voted.
Now, that bothered me.
That's a secret.
It's none of their business to know how Bob Spode voted.
I could have gotten in real good favor because I voted their way.
So we voted, no, we will not go and talk to our senior branch advisor.
Then on Friday afternoon, they changed that to about 4 or 3, 3.30, 4 o'clock.
You'll just go and talk.
You don't have to tell them how you are.
You just go and talk.
Well, it's too late to have another senior class meeting.
But we'd already voted.
We wouldn't talk to them.
So I didn't go and talk.
And so I had to appear before a board with Colonel Malloy.
And my senior transcripts of that board, there was one scared young guy up there.
Yes, sir.
No, sir.
Yes, sir.
Because my other dream had come true.
I had two dreams.
One, college I developed, get a PhD in history.
I didn't think I'd ever do it, but I took the two languages just as a possibility in the future.
Then one day I walked in ROTC and they said, and the other one was my childhood in a regular Army commission.

And they walked in and said, now if you're in the top 50% of your class, top quarter of your ROTC class, the Army started this new program called Distinguished Military Student, Distinguished Military Graduate.
And if you are in this, you can be a Distinguished Military Student.
If you maintain it, you will be called a Distinguished Military Graduate.
And at that time, the Army will tend
It's like, here are your dreams.
I mean, I had those qualities.
You mean that's all there is to it?
Yeah.
So I went out and saw Colonel Olson right after that.
And it just processed.
But I was now in danger.
I thought I might be in danger of losing that.
But it's not complying with that order.
And I got put on probation.
That's all for the semester.
And I behaved myself.
The only interesting thing that happened all year was that later he was four-star general, of course.
All right, now that march on the president's house, he didn't back down, did he?
No, no, no, no, no, no.
There was no change.
They started, the new court of court was enacted.
I mean, wasn't anything students could do about it.
No, but I do think that they could have greased the skids a little bit better ahead of time, if you understand what I mean.
I don't know, maybe they did with some of the
cadet officers like McCush and Head Ranch.
But if they did, they didn't communicate it down to the other people.
Was there anyone for you during those years that you, any senior, any faculty or staff person you talked to that you got advice, counsel from?
No, not really.
Who told you to take two languages in case you got a PhD?
I heard somewhere.
I took German and Spanish.
Looking backward, I should have taken French.
It would have been a better one.
But my father's mother, my grandmother, whom I love very dearly and who loved me, was very anti-French.
She was a German coming out of Germany right after the Franco-Prussian War.
And she endued me with a dislike for the French.
very much so, and I did not want to take French because it was rough on them.
I mean, I'm sorry, but that's the way it was.
Now, among the other changes during these years, there were lots of student wives in and around the campus, weren't there?
Yeah.
And were there more of them employed on campus?
I assume there were.
I don't know.
Were you here during the, did you go to summer, take summer classes?
No, I never took summer classes.
Okay.
When I came back after, the first year I came back, I went to ROTC summer camp.
My parents were in Germany.
My home was with an aunt down in Beaumont.
And so I kind of, she was kind of the home away from home.
And I joined the Beaumont A&M Club, I mean the Beaumont Club here at A&M.
I kind of was with it.
And then the next summer,
My aunt and I went to Germany on a freighter out of Galveston and went up to the, up the Baser River to Bremen where my father was stationed.
Now, I'm getting away from A&M, but you might find it interesting, 1936 my father was a sharecropper in Texas.
In 1946 he had a private railroad car.
He had a sergeant to take care of the railroad car.
He lived in the home of an affluent German banker.
He was lord of all he surveyed.
He commanded a battalion of railway security police over there.
He could hook that railway car to any train, go anywhere in Germany, and go with my mother, with sleepers and the whole little... And I'm assuming that he spoke German?
He spoke German.
He spoke German.
And his last name?
He never spoke English.
He never spoke a word of English until the first grade.
And that last name didn't handicap him over there?
No, no, no, no, no, no.
My, my, my.
We went to call on my grandfather's people who were left there.
Most of them were killed in Russia, they said.
One woman there had been an official photographer with the Nazi Party.
She had pictures and gave us pictures of Hitler meeting with Mussolini at Bremer Pass and things like that.
Very cold fish.
and she was very much a part of the Nazi movement.

Went out to my grandmother's place, she was definitely present, Fokker's Lair near Hammelburg, and of course they tried to call it up to my father who was in the Army of Occupation, and I went out there and visited with them too, and she was, when I say this, she was very, very, very definitely a peasant.
Alright, then you come back for your senior year in the fall of 47?
Fall of 48.
Summer of 47, RMTC at Fort Hood, summer of 48 in Germany.
Alright, now let's see, let's start making some comparisons.
There wasn't a Reveille in those years.
No, Reveille died about 43.
And the Yales and the Yale leaders and all those traditions were about what you had remembered.
What about Bonfire by 1948?
Was it bigger?
No.
Yale practice was not yet midnight Yale practice.
Only on away trips.
Oh, okay.
At midnight Yale practice, and there was a fight down in San Antonio.
I don't know if you ever heard about this one or not.
There was a riot in San Antonio because the city fathers of San Antonio refused to set a site for midnight yell practice in San Antonio.
So the yell leaders got on the marquee of a hotel in San Antonio, and the Aggies gathered there and were blocking traffic down in downtown.
And the police came, tried to break it up, and the Aggies pulled out their knives and sliced the tires of the police cars.
And they called out the National Guard.
And riot police, and they came into the triangular formation, which the Army teaches, fixed bayonets to disperse this crowd of Aggies.
We were playing Texas Tech down at the Alamo Stadium there.
And so that was, that was what they, so it did happen at the ideal practice.
I was there and I saw that.
I didn't, I wasn't right in the midst of the Aggie crowd, but I was watching it from a distance.
Do you remember whether anybody got arrested or not?
I don't remember.
I don't remember.
I came close to it because I became a little bit berserk later on as the National Guard approached me and my friends had to restrain me.
Let's see.
Of all the football games when you were an undergraduate, what was your favorite game?
Which one do you remember that you enjoyed most?
Was there a special one?
It was a very enjoyable period.
that we did not have very good teams.
Undergraduate.
I guess when we tied Texas in 1948, 14 to 14, Tom Landry was playing for Texas.
Texas had a good team.
We had not won a game.
We were nothing and nine.
and went over and tied them, and made it nothing in 9-1.
And at the same time here, there was another upset.
Navy tied Army when Army had a great team.
And that was another kind of upset.
And I thought it was kind of coincidental that the two, they were tied at the same year.
During those years, what were the most prestigious positions of student leadership that an Aggie student could have?
Could have?
And how were they selected as far as you and your buddies knew?
Was it a fair system?
Yeah.
I never heard anybody complain about it.
The person who was selected usually deserved it.
We thought.
And y'all voted.
I recognized it.
I didn't know everything in the background and all the considerations.
And was there a vote on Yale leaders?
Yeah.
And did anybody, was there even a president of the student body then?
There were class presidents.
Were you aware that there were any secret fraternities then?
As far as I know, there were no secret fraternities.
In fact, when we
It was after the war that they permitted honorary fraternities.
There was no Greek on campus.
There weren't even honorary fraternities until after war.
Does that correspond with what you know?
Y'all weren't aware of the TTs and the stickers?
Were they?
Okay.
No.
They were very secretive.
And they were...
Guyon Hall was a place where everybody went for movies and other big, were there any famous visitors in those post-war years?
Other than band leaders.
Who?
What were some of the great bands that came?
Ballman Grove, Xavier Cougon, Spike Jonze,
one of the names, Jimmy, Tommy Dorsey.
I think Tommy Dorsey came.
And the big dances were held in Sabisa?
Sabisa Hall, lovely.
And how did Aggies behave at those?
How did they treat those young ladies?
Well, I guess one of the incidents that occurred with me, I saw myself as, I loved Galahad, loved Storrs and King out there, and I read them as a kid, Book of Knowledge, and
My idea, my hero in all fiction was Galahad.
His strength was his team because his heart was pure.
And I later learned that my heart couldn't be pure, but I thought it was a good goal.
And I went to one dance over there, and I was stag.
And I saw this sloppy, drunk Aggie dancing with this nice-looking girl.
And I felt so sorry for her that he was just falling all over her and everything else.
And this is a joke on me.
I wonder what cut in on them.
I told her I felt sorry for her, and I came to her house at night coming to her rescue.
And she told me, why don't you mind your own business?
You know, that's what life's disillusioning moments.
But by and large, Aggies didn't overdrink it, though.
